</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast MRI is the most sensitive imaging modality for assessment of the nipple-areola complex (NAC), which is important both in cancer staging and in high-risk screening. However, the normal appearance of the nipple at MRI is not well defined because of a paucity of scientific literature on this topic. Hence, there is a lack of descriptive terminology and diagnostic criteria, which may account for the wide variability in interpretation among radiologists when assessing the NAC on MR images. In light of the current shift toward possible expanded use of abbreviated (ie, fast) breast MRI for screening in women at average risk for cancer in particular, and because an increasing number of women now undergo nipple-sparing mastectomy for therapeutic and/or prophylactic indications, careful assessment of the NAC at MRI is essential. In this article, the normal pattern of nipple enhancement at MRI is defined on the basis of findings observed in healthy individuals, normal nipple enhancement at MRI is correlated with the structural anatomy of the nipple at histopathologic analysis, and artifacts and pitfalls related to MRI of the NAC are reviewed. Understanding the normal range of nipple morphology and enhancement at MRI is important, as it enables radiologists to better differentiate between normal and abnormal nipple findings with increased diagnostic confidence.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div><div role="paragraph">See discussion on this article by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2019180209">Cohen and Holbrook</a>.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180039">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180039">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig1a.jpeg" height="2390" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. NAC assessment. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms of a heterogeneously dense left breast. Dense overlying breast tissue often limits mammographic assessment of the NAC because it obscures the region, as in this case. <b>(c, d)</b> On transverse US images obtained in the same patient, NAC assessment is challenging owing to varying pressure on the transducer, which may accentuate the shadowing behind the normal nipple and creates a pseudomass (arrows in <b>c</b>); in contrast, no pseudomass is seen near the contralateral nipple <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig1b.jpeg" height="2390" width="893" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. NAC assessment. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms of a heterogeneously dense left breast. Dense overlying breast tissue often limits mammographic assessment of the NAC because it obscures the region, as in this case. <b>(c, d)</b> On transverse US images obtained in the same patient, NAC assessment is challenging owing to varying pressure on the transducer, which may accentuate the shadowing behind the normal nipple and creates a pseudomass (arrows in <b>c</b>); in contrast, no pseudomass is seen near the contralateral nipple <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig1c.jpeg" height="1086" width="1932" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. NAC assessment. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms of a heterogeneously dense left breast. Dense overlying breast tissue often limits mammographic assessment of the NAC because it obscures the region, as in this case. <b>(c, d)</b> On transverse US images obtained in the same patient, NAC assessment is challenging owing to varying pressure on the transducer, which may accentuate the shadowing behind the normal nipple and creates a pseudomass (arrows in <b>c</b>); in contrast, no pseudomass is seen near the contralateral nipple <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig1d.jpeg" height="1154" width="1932" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. NAC assessment. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms of a heterogeneously dense left breast. Dense overlying breast tissue often limits mammographic assessment of the NAC because it obscures the region, as in this case. <b>(c, d)</b> On transverse US images obtained in the same patient, NAC assessment is challenging owing to varying pressure on the transducer, which may accentuate the shadowing behind the normal nipple and creates a pseudomass (arrows in <b>c</b>); in contrast, no pseudomass is seen near the contralateral nipple <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig2a.jpeg" height="1576" width="1129" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Newly diagnosed left breast cancer with invasion of the NAC in a 65-year-old woman. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> first contrast material–enhanced (postcontrast) (obtained during first phase after contrast material administration) T1-weighted MR images show left breast cancer (dashed arrow), with abnormal enhancement (solid arrow) extending contiguously from the tumor to the nipple and abnormal enhancement and thickening of the NAC (circle), consistent with invasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig2b.jpeg" height="1576" width="2021" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Newly diagnosed left breast cancer with invasion of the NAC in a 65-year-old woman. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> first contrast material–enhanced (postcontrast) (obtained during first phase after contrast material administration) T1-weighted MR images show left breast cancer (dashed arrow), with abnormal enhancement (solid arrow) extending contiguously from the tumor to the nipple and abnormal enhancement and thickening of the NAC (circle), consistent with invasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig3a.jpeg" height="1575" width="1584" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Findings after bilateral nipple-sparing mastectomy and flap reconstruction for right breast cancer and left-breast prophylaxis in a 47-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show abnormal enhancement in the native right breast, extending below the base of the nipple (solid arrows) to the junction line of the flap and native tissue (dashed arrows in <b>a</b>), consistent with recurrent cancer. The sagittal view <b>(b)</b> shows a second site of recurrence (arrowhead) at the junction line in the superoposterior region of the reconstructed right breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig3b.jpeg" height="1575" width="1566" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Findings after bilateral nipple-sparing mastectomy and flap reconstruction for right breast cancer and left-breast prophylaxis in a 47-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images show abnormal enhancement in the native right breast, extending below the base of the nipple (solid arrows) to the junction line of the flap and native tissue (dashed arrows in <b>a</b>), consistent with recurrent cancer. The sagittal view <b>(b)</b> shows a second site of recurrence (arrowhead) at the junction line in the superoposterior region of the reconstructed right breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig4a.jpeg" height="1301" width="1934" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Assessment of nipple morphology. Axial MIP images show normal symmetric everted nipples in three women <b>(a–c)</b> and normal symmetric flat nipples in a fourth woman <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig4b.jpeg" height="1301" width="1816" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Assessment of nipple morphology. Axial MIP images show normal symmetric everted nipples in three women <b>(a–c)</b> and normal symmetric flat nipples in a fourth woman <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig4c.jpeg" height="1305" width="1934" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Assessment of nipple morphology. Axial MIP images show normal symmetric everted nipples in three women <b>(a–c)</b> and normal symmetric flat nipples in a fourth woman <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig4d.jpeg" height="1305" width="1816" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Assessment of nipple morphology. Axial MIP images show normal symmetric everted nipples in three women <b>(a–c)</b> and normal symmetric flat nipples in a fourth woman <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig5a.jpeg" height="1414" width="1829" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Delineation of nipple enhancement characteristics. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the NAC (box in <b>a</b>) and the base of the nipple (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial MIP image obtained in a different woman shows the morphologic symmetry of bilateral nipples (circles). <b>(d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained in the same woman as in <b>c</b> shows the level of INE correlated with the ipsilateral BPE (box).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig5b.jpeg" height="1414" width="1922" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Delineation of nipple enhancement characteristics. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the NAC (box in <b>a</b>) and the base of the nipple (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial MIP image obtained in a different woman shows the morphologic symmetry of bilateral nipples (circles). <b>(d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained in the same woman as in <b>c</b> shows the level of INE correlated with the ipsilateral BPE (box).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig5c.jpeg" height="1360" width="1829" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Delineation of nipple enhancement characteristics. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the NAC (box in <b>a</b>) and the base of the nipple (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial MIP image obtained in a different woman shows the morphologic symmetry of bilateral nipples (circles). <b>(d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained in the same woman as in <b>c</b> shows the level of INE correlated with the ipsilateral BPE (box).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig5d.jpeg" height="1362" width="1922" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Delineation of nipple enhancement characteristics. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the NAC (box in <b>a</b>) and the base of the nipple (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Axial MIP image obtained in a different woman shows the morphologic symmetry of bilateral nipples (circles). <b>(d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained in the same woman as in <b>c</b> shows the level of INE correlated with the ipsilateral BPE (box).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig6a.jpeg" height="1408" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. SLE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of the left breast of one woman <b>(a)</b> and the right breast of another woman <b>(b)</b> show a thin rim of smooth superficial enhancement (arrows) at the level of the skin involving the NAC, with the degree of enhancement greater than that in the adjacent skin. The intensity and extent of enhancement may vary, with some enhancement involving only the nipple <b>(a)</b> and some involving the entire NAC <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig6b.jpeg" height="1408" width="1551" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. SLE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of the left breast of one woman <b>(a)</b> and the right breast of another woman <b>(b)</b> show a thin rim of smooth superficial enhancement (arrows) at the level of the skin involving the NAC, with the degree of enhancement greater than that in the adjacent skin. The intensity and extent of enhancement may vary, with some enhancement involving only the nipple <b>(a)</b> and some involving the entire NAC <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig7a.jpeg" height="1383" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. NEZ. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted breast MR images show a zone without enhancement immediately beneath the SLE. The NEZ is shown in the left breast of one woman without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> annotation (arrows) and in the right breast of another woman without <b>(c)</b> and with <b>(d)</b> annotation (arrows) to optimize visualization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig7b.jpeg" height="1383" width="1651" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. NEZ. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted breast MR images show a zone without enhancement immediately beneath the SLE. The NEZ is shown in the left breast of one woman without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> annotation (arrows) and in the right breast of another woman without <b>(c)</b> and with <b>(d)</b> annotation (arrows) to optimize visualization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig7c.jpeg" height="1347" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. NEZ. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted breast MR images show a zone without enhancement immediately beneath the SLE. The NEZ is shown in the left breast of one woman without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> annotation (arrows) and in the right breast of another woman without <b>(c)</b> and with <b>(d)</b> annotation (arrows) to optimize visualization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig7d.jpeg" height="1347" width="1651" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. NEZ. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted breast MR images show a zone without enhancement immediately beneath the SLE. The NEZ is shown in the left breast of one woman without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> annotation (arrows) and in the right breast of another woman without <b>(c)</b> and with <b>(d)</b> annotation (arrows) to optimize visualization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig8a.jpeg" height="1242" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. INE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of left <b>(a)</b> and right <b>(b–d)</b> breasts of four women show enhancement in the nipple below the NEZ and above the base of the nipple. Two patterns of internal enhancement are discernable: patchy (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and linear (arrows in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>). Internal enhancement is not always present, but when it is, it is usually equal to or less than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig8b.jpeg" height="1242" width="1654" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. INE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of left <b>(a)</b> and right <b>(b–d)</b> breasts of four women show enhancement in the nipple below the NEZ and above the base of the nipple. Two patterns of internal enhancement are discernable: patchy (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and linear (arrows in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>). Internal enhancement is not always present, but when it is, it is usually equal to or less than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig8c.jpeg" height="1145" width="1695" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. INE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of left <b>(a)</b> and right <b>(b–d)</b> breasts of four women show enhancement in the nipple below the NEZ and above the base of the nipple. Two patterns of internal enhancement are discernable: patchy (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and linear (arrows in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>). Internal enhancement is not always present, but when it is, it is usually equal to or less than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig8d.jpeg" height="1144" width="1630" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. INE. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR images of left <b>(a)</b> and right <b>(b–d)</b> breasts of four women show enhancement in the nipple below the NEZ and above the base of the nipple. Two patterns of internal enhancement are discernable: patchy (arrows in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and linear (arrows in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>). Internal enhancement is not always present, but when it is, it is usually equal to or less than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig9.jpeg" height="1419" width="2237" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Axial T1-weighted subtraction MR image of the right breast (seen in <a href="#fig5a">Figure 5a</a> and <a href="#fig5b">5b</a>) shows mild INE (arrow) compared with the BPE in the ipsilateral breast, which is also mild. The levels of INE and BPE are categorized as minimal, mild, moderate, or marked per the standardized BI-RADS lexicon for breast MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig10a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1609" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Morphologic correlation between findings in a whole-slide nipple specimen (hematoxylin-eosin stain) <b>(a)</b> and findings on the corresponding axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> of the normal nipple. The papilla (solid arrow) is the shaft of the nipple and extends above the base (dashed arrow) of an everted nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig10b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1541" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Morphologic correlation between findings in a whole-slide nipple specimen (hematoxylin-eosin stain) <b>(a)</b> and findings on the corresponding axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> of the normal nipple. The papilla (solid arrow) is the shaft of the nipple and extends above the base (dashed arrow) of an everted nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig11a.jpeg" height="1587" width="1719" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Whole-slide histologic specimen of a normal nipple <b>(a)</b> (from <a href="#fig10a">Fig 10</a>) and two orthogonally cut slices <b>(b)</b> from the specimen. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain.) The hypervascular epidermis covering the nipple corresponds to the SLE seen on MR images. The dermal layer, containing connective tissue and sebaceous glands, corresponds to the NEZ seen on MR images. The traversing ductal bundles encased in a web of smooth muscles correlate with the patchy or linear INE seen on MR images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig11b.jpeg" height="1587" width="1678" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Whole-slide histologic specimen of a normal nipple <b>(a)</b> (from <a href="#fig10a">Fig 10</a>) and two orthogonally cut slices <b>(b)</b> from the specimen. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain.) The hypervascular epidermis covering the nipple corresponds to the SLE seen on MR images. The dermal layer, containing connective tissue and sebaceous glands, corresponds to the NEZ seen on MR images. The traversing ductal bundles encased in a web of smooth muscles correlate with the patchy or linear INE seen on MR images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig12a.jpeg" height="1430" width="1694" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Paget disease of the nipple in a 72-year-old woman with an excoriated right nipple after punch biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows abnormal nipple retraction and enhancement (solid arrow) consistent with Paget disease and underlying invasive ductal carcinoma (dashed arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the nipple tissue specimen obtained at punch biopsy shows focal erosion of the nipple epidermis (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs of additional tissue specimens from this nipple, stained with hematoxylin and eosin (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and cytokeratin immunohistochemical brown stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(d)</b>, show scattered large malignant cells (arrows), also known as Paget cells, in the epidermis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig12b.jpeg" height="1430" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Paget disease of the nipple in a 72-year-old woman with an excoriated right nipple after punch biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows abnormal nipple retraction and enhancement (solid arrow) consistent with Paget disease and underlying invasive ductal carcinoma (dashed arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the nipple tissue specimen obtained at punch biopsy shows focal erosion of the nipple epidermis (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs of additional tissue specimens from this nipple, stained with hematoxylin and eosin (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and cytokeratin immunohistochemical brown stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(d)</b>, show scattered large malignant cells (arrows), also known as Paget cells, in the epidermis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig12c.jpeg" height="1212" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Paget disease of the nipple in a 72-year-old woman with an excoriated right nipple after punch biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows abnormal nipple retraction and enhancement (solid arrow) consistent with Paget disease and underlying invasive ductal carcinoma (dashed arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the nipple tissue specimen obtained at punch biopsy shows focal erosion of the nipple epidermis (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs of additional tissue specimens from this nipple, stained with hematoxylin and eosin (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and cytokeratin immunohistochemical brown stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(d)</b>, show scattered large malignant cells (arrows), also known as Paget cells, in the epidermis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig12d.jpeg" height="1212" width="1655" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span>. Paget disease of the nipple in a 72-year-old woman with an excoriated right nipple after punch biopsy. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows abnormal nipple retraction and enhancement (solid arrow) consistent with Paget disease and underlying invasive ductal carcinoma (dashed arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph of the nipple tissue specimen obtained at punch biopsy shows focal erosion of the nipple epidermis (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.) <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs of additional tissue specimens from this nipple, stained with hematoxylin and eosin (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and cytokeratin immunohistochemical brown stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(d)</b>, show scattered large malignant cells (arrows), also known as Paget cells, in the epidermis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig13a.jpeg" height="1845" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Known invasive and in situ ductal carcinoma of the left breast in a 36-year-old woman who presented for staging breast MRI. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows extensive abnormal enhancement (thick arrow) extending in a segmental distribution into the nipple (thin arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the abnormal nipple enhancement (solid arrow) to be more intense than the subjacent normal INE (dashed arrow). The SLE and NEZ are preserved. Surgical histopathologic analysis findings confirmed the diagnosis of malignant involvement of the nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig13b.jpeg" height="1845" width="1307" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Known invasive and in situ ductal carcinoma of the left breast in a 36-year-old woman who presented for staging breast MRI. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows extensive abnormal enhancement (thick arrow) extending in a segmental distribution into the nipple (thin arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows the abnormal nipple enhancement (solid arrow) to be more intense than the subjacent normal INE (dashed arrow). The SLE and NEZ are preserved. Surgical histopathologic analysis findings confirmed the diagnosis of malignant involvement of the nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig14a.jpeg" height="2198" width="1546" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) involving the right nipple and central ducts in a 68-year-old woman who presented for MRI after initial lumpectomy yielded positive surgical margins. <b>(a)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal right nipple enhancement, with complete obliteration of the normal nipple enhancement anatomy (solid arrows), as well as postsurgical change combined with residual carcinoma (dashed arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial MIP image best shows the abnormal right nipple enhancement (solid arrow) and right breast enhancement (dashed arrow), which are asymmetric with the enhancement in the normal left breast. <b>(c)</b> Histologic nipple tissue specimen subsequently obtained at mastectomy shows the corresponding histologic features of DCIS involving a large subareolar duct (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig14b.jpeg" height="1022" width="1603" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) involving the right nipple and central ducts in a 68-year-old woman who presented for MRI after initial lumpectomy yielded positive surgical margins. <b>(a)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal right nipple enhancement, with complete obliteration of the normal nipple enhancement anatomy (solid arrows), as well as postsurgical change combined with residual carcinoma (dashed arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial MIP image best shows the abnormal right nipple enhancement (solid arrow) and right breast enhancement (dashed arrow), which are asymmetric with the enhancement in the normal left breast. <b>(c)</b> Histologic nipple tissue specimen subsequently obtained at mastectomy shows the corresponding histologic features of DCIS involving a large subareolar duct (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig14c.jpeg" height="1025" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) involving the right nipple and central ducts in a 68-year-old woman who presented for MRI after initial lumpectomy yielded positive surgical margins. <b>(a)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal right nipple enhancement, with complete obliteration of the normal nipple enhancement anatomy (solid arrows), as well as postsurgical change combined with residual carcinoma (dashed arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial MIP image best shows the abnormal right nipple enhancement (solid arrow) and right breast enhancement (dashed arrow), which are asymmetric with the enhancement in the normal left breast. <b>(c)</b> Histologic nipple tissue specimen subsequently obtained at mastectomy shows the corresponding histologic features of DCIS involving a large subareolar duct (arrows). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig15a.jpeg" height="1487" width="1497" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Findings after bilateral nipple-sparing mastectomy and flap reconstruction for right breast cancer and left-breast prophylaxis in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal enhancement (solid arrows) involving a large duct of the right native nipple and extending below the nipple base to the junction line. The normal SLE (dashed arrow) along the epidermis of the nipple is preserved. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding nipple specimen photomicrograph shows ductal carcinoma in situ involving the large central duct of the nipple. The intact epidermis of the nipple is also seen. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig15b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1653" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Findings after bilateral nipple-sparing mastectomy and flap reconstruction for right breast cancer and left-breast prophylaxis in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows abnormal enhancement (solid arrows) involving a large duct of the right native nipple and extending below the nipple base to the junction line. The normal SLE (dashed arrow) along the epidermis of the nipple is preserved. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding nipple specimen photomicrograph shows ductal carcinoma in situ involving the large central duct of the nipple. The intact epidermis of the nipple is also seen. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×4.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig16a.jpeg" height="1562" width="2108" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Abnormal left-nipple enhancement in a 32-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer who presented for high-risk breast cancer screening. First postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> shows asymmetric high-intensity confluent enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) involving the base of the left nipple and corresponding to the location of a nipple piercing (arrow in <b>b</b>) seen on a craniocaudal mammogram of the left breast <b>(b)</b>. This abnormal enhancement is greater in intensity than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast and consistent with benign fibrosis related to piercing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig16b.jpeg" height="1562" width="1042" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Abnormal left-nipple enhancement in a 32-year-old woman with a family history of breast cancer who presented for high-risk breast cancer screening. First postcontrast T1-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> shows asymmetric high-intensity confluent enhancement (arrows in <b>a</b>) involving the base of the left nipple and corresponding to the location of a nipple piercing (arrow in <b>b</b>) seen on a craniocaudal mammogram of the left breast <b>(b)</b>. This abnormal enhancement is greater in intensity than the BPE in the ipsilateral breast and consistent with benign fibrosis related to piercing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig17a.jpeg" height="1179" width="1885" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Findings in a 51-year-old woman after central duct excision, who had a persistent nipple discharge, which was found at biopsy to be caused by an inflamed ectatic duct or inclusion cyst. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show a rim-enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding histologic nipple tissue specimen shows an ectatic duct or cyst with circumferential inflammatory cells and a thick rim of fibrosis, which correlates with the rim enhancement seen on the MR images. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig17b.jpeg" height="1179" width="1665" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Findings in a 51-year-old woman after central duct excision, who had a persistent nipple discharge, which was found at biopsy to be caused by an inflamed ectatic duct or inclusion cyst. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show a rim-enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding histologic nipple tissue specimen shows an ectatic duct or cyst with circumferential inflammatory cells and a thick rim of fibrosis, which correlates with the rim enhancement seen on the MR images. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig17c.jpeg" height="1335" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Findings in a 51-year-old woman after central duct excision, who had a persistent nipple discharge, which was found at biopsy to be caused by an inflamed ectatic duct or inclusion cyst. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show a rim-enhancing mass (arrow) in the left breast. <b>(c)</b> Corresponding histologic nipple tissue specimen shows an ectatic duct or cyst with circumferential inflammatory cells and a thick rim of fibrosis, which correlates with the rim enhancement seen on the MR images. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig18.jpeg" height="1158" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Motion degradation. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows bilateral ghosting artifacts of parallel structures due to motion degradation, which greatly limits evaluation of the breast parenchyma and nipple-areola regions. The nipples are the most mobile parts of the breasts and thus highly prone to motion artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig19a.jpeg" height="1004" width="1745" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Nipple malpositioning due to compression against the breast coil in three patients <i>(Pt)</i> (with <b>c</b> obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#fig18">Fig 18</a>). Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> and first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images <b>(b–d)</b> show bilateral nipples compressed against the breast coil surfaces (lines). Malpositioning of the nipples impedes the normal inflow of contrast material, limits assessment of the NAC, and can lead to development of a pseudomass (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig19b.jpeg" height="1004" width="1981" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Nipple malpositioning due to compression against the breast coil in three patients <i>(Pt)</i> (with <b>c</b> obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#fig18">Fig 18</a>). Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> and first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images <b>(b–d)</b> show bilateral nipples compressed against the breast coil surfaces (lines). Malpositioning of the nipples impedes the normal inflow of contrast material, limits assessment of the NAC, and can lead to development of a pseudomass (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig19c.jpeg" height="1144" width="1885" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Nipple malpositioning due to compression against the breast coil in three patients <i>(Pt)</i> (with <b>c</b> obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#fig18">Fig 18</a>). Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> and first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images <b>(b–d)</b> show bilateral nipples compressed against the breast coil surfaces (lines). Malpositioning of the nipples impedes the normal inflow of contrast material, limits assessment of the NAC, and can lead to development of a pseudomass (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig19d.jpeg" height="1144" width="1865" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span>. Nipple malpositioning due to compression against the breast coil in three patients <i>(Pt)</i> (with <b>c</b> obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#fig18">Fig 18</a>). Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> and first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images <b>(b–d)</b> show bilateral nipples compressed against the breast coil surfaces (lines). Malpositioning of the nipples impedes the normal inflow of contrast material, limits assessment of the NAC, and can lead to development of a pseudomass (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig20a.jpeg" height="969" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Flat and inverted nipples, which may be challenging to assess at MRI, in four women. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show flat nipples, whose enhancement anatomy may not be consistent with that of everted nipples. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show inverted nipples (circle), which may mimic enhancing masses. In such cases, comparisons with findings in the contralateral breast and prior studies are often helpful.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig20b.jpeg" height="969" width="1850" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Flat and inverted nipples, which may be challenging to assess at MRI, in four women. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show flat nipples, whose enhancement anatomy may not be consistent with that of everted nipples. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show inverted nipples (circle), which may mimic enhancing masses. In such cases, comparisons with findings in the contralateral breast and prior studies are often helpful.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig20c.jpeg" height="1074" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Flat and inverted nipples, which may be challenging to assess at MRI, in four women. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show flat nipples, whose enhancement anatomy may not be consistent with that of everted nipples. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show inverted nipples (circle), which may mimic enhancing masses. In such cases, comparisons with findings in the contralateral breast and prior studies are often helpful.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig20d.jpeg" height="1074" width="1850" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span>. Flat and inverted nipples, which may be challenging to assess at MRI, in four women. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show flat nipples, whose enhancement anatomy may not be consistent with that of everted nipples. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR images show inverted nipples (circle), which may mimic enhancing masses. In such cases, comparisons with findings in the contralateral breast and prior studies are often helpful.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig21.jpeg" height="876" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Findings in a 31-year-old woman who had a family history of breast cancer and presented for high-risk breast cancer screening. Axial first postcontrast T1-weighted subtraction MR image shows newly manifesting asymmetric enhancement (arrow) involving the lateral aspect of the left nipple. Correlation with clinical findings revealed a corresponding inflamed Montgomery gland cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig22a.jpeg" height="982" width="1786" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Benign asymmetric nipple enhancement. Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> shows slightly nodular SLE of the left nipple (dashed arrow) and smooth SLE of the right nipple (solid arrow). This asymmetry is stable, and therefore benign, compared with the asymmetric enhancement seen on an MR image obtained 3 years earlier <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig22b.jpeg" height="982" width="1964" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Benign asymmetric nipple enhancement. Axial MIP image <b>(a)</b> shows slightly nodular SLE of the left nipple (dashed arrow) and smooth SLE of the right nipple (solid arrow). This asymmetry is stable, and therefore benign, compared with the asymmetric enhancement seen on an MR image obtained 3 years earlier <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig23a.jpeg" height="2294" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Benign nipple asymmetry in a 54-year-old woman. Bilateral mediolateral oblique <b>(a, b)</b> and crandiocaudal <b>(c, d)</b> screening mammograms show a left accessory nipple (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) adjacent to the normal left nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig23b.jpeg" height="2294" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Benign nipple asymmetry in a 54-year-old woman. Bilateral mediolateral oblique <b>(a, b)</b> and crandiocaudal <b>(c, d)</b> screening mammograms show a left accessory nipple (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) adjacent to the normal left nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig23c.jpeg" height="2294" width="924" aria-labelledby="fig23c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23c</span>. Benign nipple asymmetry in a 54-year-old woman. Bilateral mediolateral oblique <b>(a, b)</b> and crandiocaudal <b>(c, d)</b> screening mammograms show a left accessory nipple (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) adjacent to the normal left nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig23c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180039/asset/images/large/rg.2019180039.fig23d.jpeg" height="2294" width="982" aria-labelledby="fig23d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23d</span>. Benign nipple asymmetry in a 54-year-old woman. Bilateral mediolateral oblique <b>(a, b)</b> and crandiocaudal <b>(c, d)</b> screening mammograms show a left accessory nipple (circle in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) adjacent to the normal left nipple.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180039&amp;id=fig23d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Fowble B, Solin LJ, Schultz DJ, Weiss MC. Breast recurrence and survival related to primary tumor location in patients undergoing conservative surgery and radiation for early-stage breast cancer. <em>Int J Radiat Oncol Biol Phys</em> 1992;23(5):933–939.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0360-3016(92)90897-Q">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1322386/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Breast+recurrence+and+survival+related+to+primary+tumor+location+in+patients+undergoing+conservative+surgery+and+radiation+for+early-stage+breast+cancer&amp;author=B+Fowble&amp;author=LJ+Solin&amp;author=DJ+Schultz&amp;author=MC+Weiss&amp;publication_year=1992&amp;journal=Int+J+Radiat+Oncol+Biol+Phys&amp;pages=933-939&amp;doi=10.1016%2F0360-3016%2892%2990897-Q&amp;pmid=1322386">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Li M, Chen K, Liu F, Su F, Li S, Zhu L. Nipple sparing mastectomy in breast cancer patients and long-term survival outcomes: an analysis of the SEER database. <em>PLoS One</em> 2017;12(8):e0183448.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0183448">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28841691/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Nipple+sparing+mastectomy+in+breast+cancer+patients+and+long-term+survival+outcomes%3A+an+analysis+of+the+SEER+database&amp;author=M+Li&amp;author=K+Chen&amp;author=F+Liu&amp;author=F+Su&amp;author=S+Li&amp;author=L+Zhu&amp;publication_year=2017&amp;journal=PLoS+One&amp;pages=e0183448&amp;doi=10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0183448&amp;pmid=28841691">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Saslow D, Boetes C, Burke W, et al. American Cancer Society guidelines for breast screening with MRI as an adjunct to mammography. <em>CA Cancer J Clin</em> 2007;57(2):75–89.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.3322/canjclin.57.2.75">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.n